{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (Laws of Manu), Chapter 1.**\n\nThis work's first chapter contains the described cosmogony. After a brief prologue in which sages approach Manu (verses 1–7), Manu narrates the Self-Existent One's creation: he produces a golden egg from seed cast into primordial waters, is born within it as Brahma, dwells a year, then splits it to form heaven and earth; later, the four *varṇas* (social orders)—Brāhmaṇa, Kṣatriya, Vaiśya, and Śūdra—emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.[^1][^2]\n\n> [p-153021] That seed became a golden egg, in splendor like the thousand-rayed sun; in it he himself was born as Brahma, the great father of all the worlds. // Mn_1.9 //  \n>   \n> [p-cd6713] After dwelling in that egg for a full year, that divine Lord, by his own contemplation, split the egg in two. // Mn_1.12 //  \n>   \n> [p-3bd729] And with those two halves he formed the heavens and the earth, and between them the middle region, the eight directions, and the eternal abode of the waters. // Mn_1.13 //[^1]  \n>   \n> [p-13a2db] And for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet. // Mn_1.31 //[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-153021).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).",
